  "text": "There are a few other groups that have looked at P. aeruginosa proteins by 2-D gel electrophoresis and other proteomic techniques. Quadroni et al. [CITATION_1] have detected 13 proteins from P. aeruginosa that were induced during sulfate starvation. Most of these proteins were identified by N-terminal Edman and MS/MS sequencing. Three classes of proteins were identified including those for solute binding, sulfonate and sulfate ester metabolism, and general stress response. These were identified by homology and localized to sulfate controlled operons on the P. aeruginosa genome. The difference in expression levels of these proteins was confirmed by RT-PCR, which indicated that repression in the presence of sulfate was at the level of transcription. The value of this approach is that changes in protein expression under certain growth conditions can be monitored. This may help to suggest the function of unknown genes as well as steps in the response to varying environmental stimuli.",
